comment:
Let's call a spade a spade, Amber Heard was initially believed when she claimed Johnny Depp abused her (even though he denied it) because of the culture we are a part of. Someone claims abuse (particularly a woman) and they are believed without question. Everybody puts so much trust into people they don't know personally and they believe everything they say, then get pissed off when they found out they've been lied to. There's a certain amount of trust you should put into serious accusations, but you should never 100% believe them until there's proof. And when it turns out that you were wrong and trusted the wrong person, own up to it. Don't go silent after you just aided to the self destruction of the true victim whose name has been dragged through the mud. 

Also wanted to note that after Depp and Heard's divorce, there was a contractual agreement that neither would speak ill of the other person after the break-up. Then, a year later, was when Heard wrote that letter to the Washington Post, "slyly" making implications that it was Depp who had supposedly abused her. But no one looks into that breach of court agreement.

comment:
I don't normally expect movie stars to be perfect people or to have perfect personal lives off-screen. It is only when they themselves start to make their personal lives an issue in a big way- either try to make themselves out as some sort as an ideal person or raise it so publicly as in this case. Frankly I even think too much attention is paid whenever a celebrity has ANY opinion on anything- the way any of us might. On the one hand everyone is curious to know their opinions as people, but then it is given far too much weight simply because they are some sort of celebrity.

On screen there are many who are really good actors, but who off-screen may or may not be good people, thoughtful people, who have their own problems and issues. We seem to want a perfect idol, not just good actors doing a good job on-screen, and they more than ever seem to get caught up in the fame fortune of their celebrity status and allow it to get to their heads.
